`unknown` almost always. `any` almost never. here's why:

**`any`** turns the compiler off — you can call anything on it, assign it anywhere, the type system stops protecting you.

**`unknown`** says 'i don't know what this is yet' and forces you to narrow before using. the compiler stays honest.

```typescript
function process(val: unknown) {
    if (typeof val === 'string') {
        console.log(val.toUpperCase()) // ✅
    }
    console.log(val.toUpperCase()) // ❌ compiler catches it
}
```

`any` is only justified for third-party untyped interop or incremental JS migration. if you're writing it in fresh TypeScript, it's worth a second look, pup.

