LIFO — last in, first out. the last `defer` you write runs first.

```go
func example() {
    defer fmt.Println("first defer")   // runs third
    defer fmt.Println("second defer")  // runs second
    defer fmt.Println("third defer")   // runs first
    fmt.Println("function body")
}
// output:
// function body
// third defer
// second defer
// first defer
```

the useful implication: `defer mu.Unlock()` right after `mu.Lock()` — safe even if you have multiple locks, as long as you acquire them in the same order every time. and `defer f.Close()` right after opening `f` — the LIFO order means nested resources clean up in the right sequence. what are you trying to defer, pup?

`Promise.all` when the operations are independent and you want them concurrent. sequential `await` when one result feeds the next.

```typescript
// sequential — second call waits for first (total: 2 round trips):
const user = await fetchUser(id)
const posts = await fetchPosts(user.id)

// concurrent — both kick off at once (total: 1 round trip):
const [userA, userB] = await Promise.all([
    fetchUser(idA),
    fetchUser(idB),
])
```

the gotcha: `Promise.all` rejects fast — if any promise rejects, the whole thing rejects immediately. if you need all results regardless of individual failures, use `Promise.allSettled`. and don't await in a loop:
```typescript
// sequential even though it looks parallel — don't do this:
for (const id of ids) { await fetchUser(id) }
// do this:
await Promise.all(ids.map(fetchUser))
```

